               <p>
            
                  <persName id="t17740706-45-person414">
                  Thomas
                   Greaves
               <interp inst="t17740706-45-person414" type="surname" value="Greaves"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t17740706-45-person414" type="given" value="Thomas"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t17740706-45-person414" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                  </persName>
            . I know nothing of the robbery, only that the piece of ribband found on the prisoner was my property.</p>
               <p>
            
                  <persName id="t17740706-45-person415">
                  John
                   Burroughs
               <interp inst="t17740706-45-person415" type="surname" value="Burroughs"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t17740706-45-person415" type="given" value="John"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t17740706-45-person415" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                  </persName>
            . The prisoner came to my master's shop, and asked for a piece of silk binding for shoes at four shillings and nine-pence the piece; while I turned about to reach some down to shew him, I saw him take a piece of ribband; then I told him we had none, and sent him to a shop over the way; I informed my mistress of it; she sent one Richardson after him; who secured him. (The ribband was produced in Court and deposed to by the prosecutor.)</p>
               <p>
            
                  <persName id="t17740706-45-person416">
                  Thomas
                   Richardson
               <interp inst="t17740706-45-person416" type="surname" value="Richardson"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t17740706-45-person416" type="given" value="Thomas"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t17740706-45-person416" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                  </persName>
            . I was sent for by Mrs. Greaves, on the 22d of June; I found the prisoner in custody; I found the ribband in his pocket and delivered it to the constable.</p>
               <p>
            
                  <persName id="t17740706-45-person417">
                  Robert
                   Moore
               <interp inst="t17740706-45-person417" type="surname" value="Moore"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t17740706-45-person417" type="given" value="Robert"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t17740706-45-person417" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                  </persName>
             I am a constable: I was sent for by Mr. Greaves; the ribband was delivered to me, and I kept it till the day the bill was found; then I delivered it to the prosecutor.</p>
               <p>Q. to Burroughs. Is that the ribband that was delivered to the constable?</p>
               <p>Burroughs. Yes.</p>
               <p>Prisoner's Defence.</p>
               <p>I picked up the ribband as I crossed the way; I put it in my pocket; I did not know what it was; as I was going home the boy laid hold of me; and said I had stole something; I never stole any thing in my life.</p>
               <p>
                  <xptr type="pageFacsimile" doc="177407060048"></xptr>The prisoner called four witnesses who gave him a very good character.</p>
